<F P=101> BRAZIL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Highway Police Seize 10 Kg of Cocaine, Arrest Bolivian </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY0703181594 Brasilia Radio Nacional da Amazonia Network in 
Portuguese 1000 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY0703181594 </F>
<F P=104>  Brasilia Radio Nacional da Amazonia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Santos Mario in Campo Grande] </F>
  [Text] In Mato Grosso do Sul State, the federal highway 
police have seized another 10 kg of high-quality cocaine that 
were being carried to Sao Paulo in hidden compartments built 
into an Opala [a Brazilian-made Chevrolet model] trunk. 
  The cocaine shipment was intended for the Nigerian 
connection 
in Sao Paulo State. The arrest of a Bolivian citizen indicates 
a new tactic by the traffickers on the Bolivia-Sao Paulo route. 
  Antonio Omar Sanchez, a Bolivian merchant living in Sao 
Paulo, is under arrest. He was caught during a routine 
operation carried out by the federal highway police on the 
BR-262 Highway. 
  In the federal highway police's opinion, impaired by 
successive arrests in which people were caught red-handed, the 
Nigerian connnection is reportedly using people who do not look 
so suspicious to carry the drug. Antonio Omar Sanchez was sent 
to the federal police and indicted for being caught red-handed 
in a crime. 

</TEXT>

