<H3> <TI>   Justice Minister Interviewed on Surrender of Drug Trafficker Urdinola </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1203185194 Santa Fe de Bogota Emisoras Caracol Network in 
Spanish 1745 GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1203185194 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Emisoras Caracol Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Justice Minister Andres Gonzalez Diaz by </F>
unidentified Caracol announcer in Santa Fe de Bogota on 12 
March--live] 
  [Text] Announcer: What is the government's 
position on the surrender of Valle del Cauca drug traffickers, 
which began today with the surrender of Julio Fabio Urdinola 
Grajales? 
  Gonzalez: I think this is an important event in 
the fight against drug trafficking and a positive event in the 
struggle against crime. It conveys the idea that criminals are 
better off surrendering to justice rather than succumbing to the 
state's firm actions. To the extent that this process advances 
within the framework of effective cooperation so justice can be 
done, we believe it will help strengthen the country's judicial 
organization. 
  Announcer: Is the government certain that drug 
traffickers who surrender will confess their crimes and 
cooperate with justice? 
  Gonzalez: According to reports from the 
Prosecutor General's Office, we understand there is a 
willingness on the part of drug traffickers to cooperate with 
authorities and confess their crimes. Obviously, this will have 
to be evaluated and judged by the Prosecutor General's Office 
and judicial authorities. However, we do have reports on the 
drug traffickers' willingness to cooperate. They surrendered to 
authorities unconditionally. Let's wait for an evaluation from 
the Prosecutor General's Office and for the process to conclude. 
  Announcer: Is the Palmira Prison a maximum 
security prison? Does it guarantee that these people will be 
safe there? 
  Gonzalez: Once we received the information from 
the Prosecutor General's Office on the surrender of these 
individuals, we set aside a place within Palmira Prison and took 
special security measures. They will be submitted to an ordinary 
disciplinary regime, as well as to special security measures. 
  Once the projects for a security section within Palmira 
Prison are complete, they will be transferred to those 
installations. 
  Announcer: Does the government know anything about 
other people surrendering? 
  Gonzalez: No. There are no reports of other drug 
traffickers surrendering to justice. As the public knows, this 
surrender is part of a process of conversations and requests 
that has been under way for several months now under the 
direction of the Prosecutor General's Office. 
  Announcer: We thank Justice Minister Andres 
Gonzalez Diaz. He just gave the government's official position 
on the surrender of Julio Fabio Urdinola Grajales. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

