<H3> <TI>   De Greiff's Meeting With Cali Cartel Lawyers Bumped by `Surprise' DEA Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0903015694 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0000 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0903015694 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report from the "24 Hours" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The prosecutor general's [Gustavo de Grieff] 
questionable situation moved into even deeper water this 
afternoon. When he was about to meet with Cali Cartel lawyers, 
he received a surprise visit by the DEA director in Colombia. 
  Attorney Bernardo Gonzalez, representative of Gilberto 
Rodriguez Orejuela, and Attorney Juan Fernandez Carrasquilla, 
representative of Julio Fabio Ordinola Grajales, arrived this 
afternoon at the Prosecutor General's Office to confirm that 
their intentions to surrender remain firm. Although the slated 
meeting did not take place because de Grieff left hastily to 
meet with President Cesar Gaviria, the visit of the DEA director 
in Colombia caused surprise. Authorized Prosecutor General's 
Office spokesmen said it was regrettable that the U.S. 
Government, through the DEA, meddles in the surrender process. 
According to the attorneys, the Colombian Government has not 
allowed the surrender. 
  [Begin recording] 
  Fernandez: In our opinion, the delay is the 
government's fault. 
  Unidentified reporter: Why? 
  Fernandez: Because the government has not decided 
yet to guarantee the jail. Before any more steps are taken in 
the negotiations, the Justice Ministry must guarantee the 
Prosecutor General's Office that the inmates will not be moved 
from the place where they surrender. [end recording] 
  To conclude, the attorneys said that their clients' 
surrender 
will be done individually and not in the name of the drug cartel. 

</TEXT>

