<F P=101> COSTA RICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   DITA Investigates `Suspicious Importation' of Potential Precursor Chemical </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0703035694 San Jose LA REPUBLICA in Spanish 28 Feb 94 p 12a </F>
<F P=103> PA0703035694 </F>
<F P=104>  San Jose LA REPUBLICA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Basilio Quesada Chanto] </F>
  [Text] The Technical Customs Investigations Division (DITA) 
is investigating the suspicious importation of large quantities 
of isopropyl alcohol [alcohol hidropropilico] not only for 
possible fiscal irregularities but also for potential links to 
drug trafficking activities. 
  This chemical substance presumably can be used to process 
cocaine, "crack," and other drugs, thus DITA personnel suspect 
that a cocaine laboratory may be operating in the country. 
According to the police report, this type of alcohol, which was 
presumably shipped from El Salvador, cannot be used for medical 
or industrial (liquor production) purposes. Furthermore, it is 
described as a solvent on the list of suspected precursor 
chemicals. 
  DITA grew even more suspicious when Costa Rican authorities 
called the Salvadoran firm noted as the shipper on the customs 
entry document, and the firm said it does not distribute that 
type of product. 
  DITA will coordinate the case with the Government and Public 
Security Ministry's national drug control directorate as there 
is enough evidence to suggest that a cocaine laboratory is 
behind the importing firm. The latter is believed to be a ghost 
company as it does not have any physical location or personnel 
to handle the alcohol it has brought into the country. The 
company has imported more than 40,000 liters of isopropyl 
alcohol from October 1993 to date. The final destination of the 
chemical is unknown. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

