<F P=101> HAITI </F>
<H3> <TI>   Radio Reports Cocaine, Marijuana Seizures </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL0703233494 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1700 
GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0703233494 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A ship arriving in Haiti under a Honduran flag was 
inspected by the U.S. Coast Guard, which discovered about 100 kg 
of cocaine on board. They arrested the 15 members of the crew. 
The drug was discovered inside a container during the 
preliminary search at the U.S. Naval Base at Guantanamo Bay, 
Cuba. The ship was due for a more thorough search on 6 March 
upon its landing in the Florida Everglades. Of the 15 people 
arrested, 12 are of Colombian nationality and the three others 
are from Peru. Their identities were not revealed. 
  Twelve kg of cocaine concealed in plastic containers was 
intercepted on 5 March at the international airport. The 
national anti-drug brigade proceeded to arrest the two 
smugglers, a U.S. citizen of Haitian origin and a Haitian woman 
named Joanne Francois. The drug seized at the airport is 
assessed at 12 kg. 
  Furthermore, a small boat carrying 50 bags of marijuana 
wrecked in Torbeck in the Port-Salut region and was discovered 
by the anti-drug brigade. However, the smuggler was concealed by 
the population that had seized the boat. Two men from Colombia, 
who were still aboard the boat, were arrested. 

</TEXT>

