<F P=101> PANAMA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cordero Says DEA Role in Investigations Not Violating Country's Sovereignty </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0803154394 Panama City LA PRENSA in Spanish 8 Mar 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PA0803154394 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA PRENSA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Manuel Alvarez Cedeno] </F>
  [Text] Deputy Foreign Minister Carlos Cordero has reported 
that the Panamanian Government is cooperating with the DEA in 
the investigation of crimes related to drug trafficking. 
  The DEA dismantled a drug trafficking ring that laundered 
more than $10 million and was made up of Panamanian and 
Colombian lawyers, accountants, and businessmen. Cordero said 
that there is cooperation with DEA authorities to investigate 
drug related crimes. The diplomat said that he agrees with 
acting Attorney General Bolivar Davalos on the rules for this 
cooperation and added that the Foreign Relations Ministry will 
collaborate in this regard. 
  Cordero said that DEA participation in investigations 
related 
to drug trafficking do not violate the country's sovereignty as 
long as Panama grants authorization as a sovereign country, 
which it is. 
  The investigations indicate that distributors in this 
network 
introduced large amounts of cocaine into the United States from 
Colombia and Panama. The deputy foreign minister pointed out 
that DEA agents no longer participate in searches or arrests in 
Panama, leaving these tasks to Panamanian authorities. 

</TEXT>

