<F P=100> NEAR EAST &amp; SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> INDIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gujarat Reportedly Becoming a `Haven' for Drug Traffickers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94WD0238A New Delhi PATRIOT in English 24 Jan 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> 94WD0238A </F>
<F P=104>  New Delhi PATRIOT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:CSO 

  [Text] Ahmedabad, Jan 23--Gujarat is fast becoming a haven 
for drug traffickers as a result of the sealing of the Punjab 
and Jammu and Kashmir borders with Pakistan. 
  The Seizure of 1,600 kg of mandrax tablets valued at Rs 2.5 
crore, by the Directorate of Revenue Intelligence (DRI) from a 
godown at Gota village near Ahmedabad last week is an 
eye-opener. DRI officials also got the clue that the drug 
traffickers were operating systematically in the city. They had 
manufactured mandrax tablets outside the city and were using 
local agents for the distribution of the tablets in other parts 
of the State. 
  Dr. Yusuf Merchant, honorary director of the Drug Abuse 
Information Rehabilitation and Research Centre (DAIRRC) of 
Bombay, recently met about 10,000 drug addicts in Gujarat and 
Bombay during the course of their rehabilitation camps. 
  The number of drug addicts in Gujarat has risen from 800 in 
1989 to a staggering 70,000 in 1993. According to a survey 
conducted by DAIRRC, every year about 4,500 more people in the 
State are becoming drug addicts. About 400 drug addicts from the 
State had undergone treatment for de-addiction at DAIRRC in the 
last three years. 
  About 5,000 cases of de-addiction have been registered with 
the Gujarat Kelavni Trust in the last five years. The DAIRRC 
survey said about 75,000 drug addicts belonged to four major 
cities. Out of this, Ahmedabad accounts for 30,000 cases, 
followed by Baroda 20,000, Surat 17,000 and Rajkot 13,000. 
  Drug addiction has been detected among prisoners of the 
Sabarmati central jail in Ahmedabad, according to the survey 
made by the Gujarat Kelavni Trust, Dr Nathubhai Patel, honorary 
director of the trust," said "a day care centre" had been set up 
in the prison by the trust to study the drug addiction habits 
among the prisoners, social workers visit the jail once in a 
week to motivate the prisoners against falling prey to drug 
addiction. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

