<F P=101> LIBYA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Convicted Drug Dealers Could Face Death Sentences </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0603160294 Paris AFP in English 1533 GMT 6 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0603160294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tripoli, March 6 (AFP)--Convicted drug dealers and 
producers will be treated as spies and could face the death 
sentence following a change in the law here, an official said 
Sunday [6 March]. 
  The law was amended to say that "any activities linked to 
drug production, manufacture or trade, will be considered as 
conniving with the enemy," the source said. 
  Those found guilty of espionage already risk the death 
penalty, but convicted drug dealers previously only faced jail 
sentences. 
  Drug addicts are not affected by the change, and if found 
guilty still face a maximum penalty of imprisonment for 
rehabilitation programmes, the official added. 
  Libyan leader Mu'ammar Qadhdhafi accused the United States 
and Israel in January of propagating drugs in Arab countries in 
"a cold war aimed at destroying them." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

