<F P=101> CAYMAN ISLANDS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Four Jamaicans Charged Following Seizure of Over 350 Lbs of Marijuana </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94WD0258C Georgetown GUYANA CHRONICLE in English 4 Jan 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> 94WD0258C </F>
<F P=104>  Georgetown GUYANA CHRONICLE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:CSO 

  [Text] George Town, Grand Cayman, Cayman Islands (CANA) -- 
Four Jamaican nationals living in the Cayman Islands were 
charged Tuesday with a variety of drug offences after police 
seized more than 350 pounds of marijuana over the New Year's 
weekend. 
  The four are Robert Everton Neil and Robert Gammon, both of 
St. Elizabeth, Jamaica and Seaford John Singh and Stalinova 
Singh, husband and wife from Clarendon. 
  All four were charged with possession of a controlled drug 
with intent to supply along with simple possession. 
  Prosecuting Attorney (Crown Counsel) Adam Roberts said the 
foursome were part of a sophisticated operation, headed by Neil 
in the Cayman Islands, with an "origination" in Jamaica. 
  Magistrate Peter Jackson denied bail for the four, despite 
the pleas from Mrs. Singh that she had six children in Jamaica 
and needed to care for them. 
  Bail was denied on the grounds the defendents would likely 
leave the island as they have few local ties, Jackson said. 
  The 352 pounds of marijuana seized by Drugs Squad officers 
has an estimated street value of US$450,000, said Drugs Squad 
superintendent Trevor Cutts. 
  Cutts has not ruled out further arrests in the ongoing case 
and has said he is pursuing leads on how drugs are getting from 
Jamaica to Cayman. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

