<F P=101> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Valades Says Efforts To Combat Drug Trafficking, Money Laundering To Be `Intensified' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94WB0029C Mexico City EXCELSIOR in Spanish 24 Feb 94 pp 5-A, 
32-A </F>

<F P=103> 94WB0029C </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City EXCELSIOR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:CSO 

  [Excerpts] Culiacan, Sinaloa, 23 February -- The attorney 
general of the republic, Diego Valades Rios, declared: "The 
Mexican Government will not close its eyes to reality, nor deny 
the phenomenon of violence. However, skepticism claiming that 
crime cannot be defeated is not advisable either." [passage 
omitted] 
  He indicated that the Office of the Attorney General of the 
Republic [PGR] will maintain a single response for gaining 
society's confidence: working with resolve and integrity. By 
doing so, it will eventually succeed in addressing the demand 
for a reduction in crime. 
  He remarked that the efforts to combat the drug traffic, and 
to punish "money laundering," would be intensified "as an 
international commitment for Mexico." In the border zones, the 
Federal Judicial Police (PJF) and customs' agents will devote 
more effort to detecting smuggled firearms. They will go to 
great lengths to combat impunity, and will continue to oversee 
the conduct of PJF members and PGR employees. Moreover, those 
dismissed for committing crimes will not be reinstated. [passage 
omitted] 
  As for the battle against the drug traffic, he claimed that 
the statistics prove the country's effort in this regard, adding 
that, in response to Mexico's recommendation that the demand for 
drugs be attacked as well, the United States Government has 
announced changes in its strategy for eradicating drug 
consumption. [passage omitted] 
  Finally, he announced that the investigations of the 
assassination of Cardinal Juan Jesus Posadas Ocampo have made 
great progress: 35 persons have been arrested and brought to 
trial, and there are 13 arrest warrants to be executed. 

</TEXT>

