<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Navy Speedboats To Patrol Caribbean for Drugs </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94WB0029F Mexico City EXCELSIOR STATES SECTION in Spanish 25 
Feb 94 pp 1, 4 </F>

<F P=103> 94WB0029F </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City EXCELSIOR STATES SECTION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Violeta Pacheco] </F>
  [Text] Veracruz, Ver., 24 February -- The Navy Secretariat 
will assign four superpowered speedboats permanently to 
reinforce the surveillance in the Caribbean zone, a route on 
which drug trafficking to the United States is occurring. This 
announcement was made here today by the commander of the gulf 
and Caribbean Sea Naval Force, Mariano Francisco Saynez Mendoza. 
  He reported that three of these four units (manufactured in 
New Orleans) are currently operating in the gulf and Caribbean 
area for a training phase. In March, they will initiate the 
permanent surveillance. 
  Saynez Mendoza revealed that, in the surveillance operations 
conducted in the Caribbean zone, an abandoned ship carrying 1.5 
tons of cocaine was detected. As a result, the vessel was turned 
over to the Cozumel Island sector, to be consigned to the 
pertinent authorities. 
  He claimed that drug trafficking by sea has declined 
considerably, although the Caribbean area is, of course, still a 
troubled area. It is considered a traditional route for the drug 
traffic from Central and South American countries to the United 
States. 
  Stressing that the majority of vessels come from Colombia, 
Venezuela, and the Grand Cayman Islands, where these boats are 
detected while attempting to transport the drugs to the border, 
he admitted that there are, of course, some of other 
nationalities. 
  He concluded by noting that, at present, the No. 51 patrol 
boat, Isla Coronado, the No. 52, Isla Lobos, and the No. 53, 
Isla Guadalupe, are in this port for a training period. It will 
be the No. 54 patrol boat, Isla Cozumel, that will be 
commissioned in March. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

