<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Over 50 Kg of Ephedrine Seized at Tijuana Bus Terminal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94WB0029H Mexico City EXCELSIOR in Spanish 26 Feb 94 p 41-A </F>
<F P=103> 94WB0029H </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City EXCELSIOR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:CSO 

  [Text] Over 50 kg of the chemical precursor, ephedrine, 
worth more than 300,000 new pesos on the narcotics black market, 
was confiscated by the Office of the Attorney General of the 
Republic. This was achieved through an operation conducted in 
the town of Tijuana, Baja California, during which Federal 
Judicial Police agents captured two presumed drug dealers 
attempting to smuggle the shipment into the United States. 
  The ephedrine, a chemical component essential for processing 
cocaine base and producing amphetamines, was being transported 
by Martin Flores and Carlos Denis Diaz, who had received the 
product from Guadalajara, Jalisco. There is another individual 
implicated in trafficking with this drug, named "Ezequiel," who 
is now being sought by federal agents. 
  The drugs were located in the parcel section of the Tijuana 
Bus Terminal. The two presumed drug dealers went there, picking 
up the drugs to be delivered and later smuggled into the United 
States. 
  When making their preliminary statements, the subjects under 
arrest admitted that this was the fifth time that they had 
engaged in this type of work, claiming that they were each to 
receive $500 for the service. 
  The Federal Public Prosecutor's Office ordered a detailed 
investigation to locate the one or more owners of the chemical, 
which is used for the so-called "cuts" in cocaine, providing the 
drug with a greater stimulating potential. 
  Based on the investigations being conducted by the social 
representative, it will be determined today whether the two 
presumed accused have connections with cocaine distribution 
rings established in Mexico and the United States. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

