<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> PANAMA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Travelers Must Declare Cash, `Liquid Assets' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1503174394 Panama City LA PRENSA in Spanish 11 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1503174394 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA PRENSA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Ibeth Vega G.] </F>
  [Text] President Guillermo Endara's government has 
approved, through an Executive decree, the obligation of every 
person who enters the country to declare under oath how much 
cash or liquid assets they are bringing with them. According to 
the decree, the measure will control the entrance of fiduciary 
money, "since right now, a great many people enter the nation 
with large amounts of cash and other assets and no one knows 
their origin or destination." 
  Several weeks ago, DEA agents in the United States said 
Panama cooperated more in the fight against drug trafficking 
during Manuel Antonio Noriega's military dictatorship than the 
current democratic government. 
  According to a Presidency press bulletin, the government 
order seeks to safeguard the principles ruling the International 
Financial Center operating in Panama and to prevent the 
fraudulent entrance of ill gotten cash and other valuables. In 
this regard, the document indicates that "although our 
legislation does not prohibit the entrance and exit of cash and 
other liquid assets, it is advisable to safeguard the Panamanian 
banking center's principles. This assures that passengers 
entering the nation with cash and other assets, that the cash 
and assets have legal origins and are not the product of illegal 
drug trafficking." 
  The government said the Customs Directorate will be 
responsible for enforcing the decree as well as punishing the 
violators. Forms, therefore will be drawn up to read: 
"Traveler's Sworn Statement," in which the person, national or 
foreigner, will declare his assets. 
  Yesterday, members of the National Banking Association 
pointed out that the initiative can be healthy, but only as a 
precautionary measure as it is very difficult to prevent money 
laundering. Meanwhile, others said the measures could cause the 
number of attacks on tourists to increase as the amount of cash 
being brought in will be known. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-21930 </DOCNO>
