<F P=100> NEAR EAST &amp; SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> PAKISTAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   End of Narcotics Control Board Welcomed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1303122394 Rawalpindi JANG in Urdu 12 Mar 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> BK1303122394 </F>
<F P=104>  Rawalpindi JANG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Urdu </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Editorial: "Winding Up the Narcotics Control Board"] </F>
  [Text] Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto has issued orders to 
dismantle the Pakistan Narcotics Control Board [PNCB] with 
immediate effect and to make it a part of the National Narcotics 
Control Agency in the wake of the board's failure to check 
narcotics smuggling. The chairman of the PNCB has been removed 
from his current post and appointed as an officer on special 
duty, while Major Salahuddin Ghazi, the director general of the 
Antinarcotics Task Force, has been temporarily appointed as 
chairman of the PNCB [sentence as published]. 
  In view of the large funds provided to the PNCB and wide 
powers given to it, one would have rightly expected that the 
board would play a very important role in checking smuggling and 
the growth of the narcotics menace. The PNCB has not only 
miserably failed in achieving the targets and objectives, but 
some of its officials have also been found to be involved in the 
narcotics trade. Several domestic and foreign agencies have 
vehemently criticized its performance. Under these 
circumstances, even the general public was questioning the 
justification for the continued existence of the PNCB in view of 
its miserable performance despite such a formidable amount of 
money invested in it. Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto has taken 
an important step by disbanding the PNCB, which was an 
inevitable step in the interest of the nation and the country. 
However, the new task force set up to control narcotics 
smuggling needs to be made so effective that its solid 
performance in eliminating drug smuggling should by itself 
become visible to the public. A close watch should also be kept 
on the officials of the task force, so that they remain free of 
all the shortcomings, weaknesses, and corruptions that led to 
the dissolution of the Pakistan Narcotics Control Board. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

