<F P=101> DENMARK </F>
<H3> <TI>   Man Arrested at German Border With 100 Kg of Hashish </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P20504A Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE in Danish 17 Feb 94 
p 6 </F>

<F P=103> 94P20504A </F>
<F P=104>  Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Danish </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [RITZAUS Bureau report: "Man Arrested With 100 Kilograms of </F>
Hashish"] 
  [Excerpts] A 36-year-old man was found out at the 
Danish-German border when he tried to smuggle around lOO kg of 
hashish from Germany into Denmark. This is the largest hashish 
seizure that police and customs officials have made in recent 
years. 
  The 36-year-old, who is an Icelandic citizen, is being held 
for preliminary investigation in Grasten. The criminal police in 
Aabenraa have charge of the investigation. [passage omitted] 
Icelandic police revealed that the man has lived in Spain for a 
number of years, and that earlier he had been convicted for drug 
smuggling in both Iceland and Great Britain. 
  The finding of the 100 kg of hashish in the man's baggage is 
the biggest single seizure at the Danish-German border in recent 
years. For all of 1993 only around 30 kg were seized at the 
border. The two preceding years, customs and police officials 
found about 400 kg of hashish. 
  Reduced customs inspection at the border following Denmark's 
joining the Internal Market in 1993 was named by the chief of 
the Sonderborg Customs and Taxation Region as the reason for 
authorities more rarely uncovering attempts at narcotics 
smuggling. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

