<H3> <TI>   Seizures of LSD Becoming More Common in Coastal Region </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94WD0246B Buenos Aires LA PRENSA in Spanish 6 Feb 94 p 11 </F>
<F P=103> 94WD0246B </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires LA PRENSA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Article: "Cocaine and LSD"] </F>
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] Mar del Plata--While most of 
the drugs seized by the police so far this season were cocaine, 
a new feature in this area was the confiscation of lysergic acid 
[LSD], a substance "not well known" to date in this city, said 
the authorities. 
  LSD, an expensive drug sold in very tiny amounts, "was not 
well known in the region" until this season. It has been seized 
in "private homes of people involved in drug trafficking," said 
the head of Mar del Plata's Drug Traffic Division, 
Superintendent Alejandro Redik. 
  The police officer did not reveal the exact amount of LSD 
that was seized due to "the court proceedings, at the wishes of 
the judge handling the case," he explained. 
  "There was a great deal of antidrug activity in January: 
about 20 arrests, seizures of cocaine, marijuana, and LSD," he 
said. 
  The constant rise in the drug traffic in Argentina has been 
shown by "the 30 percent increase in drug seizures" in relation 
to past years, according to the general superintendent, Horacio 
Hernandez. 
  "Obviously, if there is more traffic it is because demand 
and 
consumption are both up. And if there are more drug seizures, it 
is reasonable to say that there is also increased police 
vigilance," both police officers agreed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

