<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> BOLIVIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vice President Gore's Refusal To Wear Coca Leaf Necklace Interpreted as `Snub' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2103021894 Havana Cuba Vision Network in Spanish 0100 GMT 
21 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2103021894 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Cuba Vision Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] U.S. Vice President Al Gore removed a coca leaf 
necklace that had been placed in homage around his neck upon his 
arrival at the airport in La Paz, capital of Bolivia. The 
incident was interpreted by Bolivian radio as an inadmissable 
snub, a grave insult to Bolivia, because the coca leaf is 
considered an element of the national culture. 
  The U.S. vice president's attitude is due to Washington's 
position that the origin of the drug-addiction problem affecting 
U.S. society lies in the existence of the coca leaf. 
  The coca leaf has been consumed for centuries for beneficial 
purposes, but now the U.S. is trying to bring about the total 
elimination of the plant. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-22009 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "jptdd013__l94012" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   JPRS-tdd-94-013-L </AU>
Document Type:JPRS 
Document Title:Narcotics 

<DATE1>  2 March 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> BOLIVIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Defends `Traditional Use' of Coca Leaf </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1803233594 La Paz PRESENCIA in Spanish 2 Mar 94 p 7 </F>
<F P=103> PY1803233594 </F>
<F P=104>  La Paz PRESENCIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] On 1 March, the government made an energetic 
defense of the traditional use of coca leaf, and it rejected the 
proposal by the UN International Drug Control Board (JIFE) that 
Bolivia and Peru should declare illegal the cultivation and use 
of coca leaf in all its forms. 
  Through an official document, the Foreign Ministry reminded 
JIFE that Bolivia "acknowledges as legal the traditional use" of 
coca leaf. Vice President Victor Hugo Cardenas stated that 
"Bolivia is a sovereign country," where there is a law that 
differentiates between the legal and illegal use of coca leaf. 
  "I believe that Bolivia demands respect for its laws and 
sovereignty. Coca leaf will continue to exist because a large 
part of the country uses it for medicinal, healing, and 
cultural rituals," Cardenas said. 
  Foreign Minister Antonio Arinibar reported that the case of 
excessive coca leaf production has caused a conflictive 
situation due to the process of the change in governments. 
  "The basis of the government's policy is that of voluntary 
eradication in coordination with a responsive and joint effort 
with the producers," he said. 
  Regarding the eradication of coca and the latest incidents 
in 
Chapare, Felix Santos, executive secretary of the General Trade 
Union Confederation of Peasant Workers of Bolivia, stated that 
this sector wants to live in peace, not under a regime of 
violence. "But the government causes violence by forcefully 
eradicating coca plantations that are the only economic support 
for the workers in Cochabamba's tropical region," he said. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

