<F P=102>  PA2303023394 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0000 GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2303023394 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "24 Hours Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] There are more statements by Prosecutor General de 
Greiff, who was unruffled by the U.S. announcement of a possible 
suspension of judicial cooperation with Colombia. 
  Although the Governments of the United States and Colombia 
have not made official the suspension of aid or the exchange of 
judicial evidence, the prosecutor general noted that if the 
warning is carried out his office will continue to try the 
narcotraffickers with the evidence that it gathers. 
  [Begin recording] [De Greiff] Nobody benefits. Nobody 
benefits from a lack of evidence exchange or a lack of 
cooperation. 
  [Unidentified reporter] Who stands to lose the most or what 
happens? 
  [De Greiff] I believe that the United States stands to lose 
the most. 
  [Reporter] Mr. Prosecutor, who do you think is--let us speak 
honestly--trying to trip you up? 
  [De Greiff] Ask the government. 
  [Reporter] Do you think it is necessary to reform the law on 
criminal proceedings again? 
  [De Greiff] I think that no foreign country has the right to 
indicate to another one how to dictate its laws. That is the 
mission of the legislators. [end recording] 
  [Earlier in this same "24 Hours Newscast" Santa Fe de Bogota 
Inravision Television Cadena 1 in Spanish at 0000 GMT on 23 
March also carries a three-minute report on press agency reports 
that the United States may suspend judicial cooperation with 
Colombia and U.S. State Department sources claiming there is 
very little behind these rumors. Colombian Embassy sources said 
that future cooperation is being assessed and "whether material 
would be given to the office of Prosecutor General de Greiff in 
the future." In a recording, when asked about this issue 
Colombian Foreign Minister Neomi Sanin said: "Colombia has a 
sovereign and independent policy. It has its own foreign policy 
that is respected by all countries of the hemisphere."] 

