<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> COLOMBIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Attorney General Denies Reports of U.S. Judicial Aid Freeze </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2003193294 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1800 GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2003193294 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "NTC News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] A few minutes ago, Attorney General Gustavo Arrieta 
said it is not true that the United States has stopped sending 
evidence in conjunction with the Medellin Cartel surrender 
process in Colombia. International wire services have, over the 
past few hours, reported that the U.S. State Department will no 
longer cooperate with Colombian justice. 
  [Begin recording] [Unidentified reporter] Mr. Attorney 
General, what is the official information or reaction to reports 
by international wire services that U.S. legal assistance to 
Colombia has been suspended? 
  [Arrieta] Diego, the information I have from Colombian 
authorities is that this is not true. 
  [Reporter] Where could this information have originated 
then? 
  [Arrieta] I do not know. I think there are too many 
misunderstandings on this topic, too many unverified reports 
circulating. The truth is that the news could have come from any 
of these confusing reports. I reiterate, however, that according 
to the information I have, this is not true. 
  [Reporter] Mr. Prosecutor, what is the situation right now 
regarding U.S.-Colombian relations in conjunction with 
exchanging legal information relating to drug trafficking? 
  [Arrieta] These past few weeks we have talked with the U.S. 
State Department through the U.S. Embassy and with the support 
of the Colombian Government. The idea is to bolster this process 
because we believe that it continues to be fundamental for 
carrying out surrender policies and legal actions in Colombia. I 
do not think there is any sense in denying that relations have 
been tense and difficult, but we are working on this and I hope 
it turns out well and we will be able to rebuild the judicial 
cooperation program. 
  [Reporter] Does cooperation continue despite current 
problems? 
  [Arrieta] Yes, we have received cooperation these past few 
days. Obviously, the intensity and level has dropped 
significantly, but I repeat, I believe it will recover. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

