<H3> <TI>   Drug Money Reportedly `Flooding' Nation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2403213394 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2403213394 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] Fedesarrollo [Foundation for Higher Education and 
Development] has sounded the alarm: Drug trafficking money is 
flooding Colombia. Money laundering is at the wholesale level 
here. The measures adopted to control money laundering equally 
affect legitimate businessmen. 
  [Begin recording] [Unidentified reporter] About $4 billion 
from drug trafficking reportedly arrives in the country each 
year. The most common method to introduce money is through 
construction, cars, and many consumption goods like food and 
presents. 
  [Fedesarrollo President Eduardo Lora] Almost every product 
can be imported by purchasing it abroad using foreign currency 
that was bought at very low exchange rates and used as money 
laundering mechanisms. 
  [Reporter] The National Superintendency of Banks and the 
National Customs and Tax Directorate are currently investigating 
some 5,300 violations of foreign exchange guidelines that 
businessmen, importers, and even banks have concocted. At least 
90 percent of them are supposedly involved in money laundering. 
  [Bank Superintendent Jose Elias Melo] Financial institutions 
are frequently involved in money laundering operations because 
they handle money. 
  [Lora] The attraction stems from the slowness of the 
devaluation process, which makes stashing money in Colombia more 
profitable than stashing it abroad. 
  [Reporter] Colombia lacks legislation to control money 
laundering. Meanwhile, measures to restrain lawful money, such 
as credit restrictions, affect drug traffickers and legitimate 
businessmen equally. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

