<H3> <TI>   Presidential Candidates Support Maintaining Prosecutor General's Office </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2303201394 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2303201394 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The National Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] Prosecutor General Gustavo de Greiff Restrepo has 
made his mark on his post. In spite of the fact he has turned 
out to be quite controversial, the presidential candidates do 
not dare touch that office. 
  [Begin recording] [Liberal Party Candidate Ernesto Samper 
Pizano] I would reform the administrative aspect, but under no 
circumstances would I lessen the authority of the prosecutor as 
the top official for investigating crimes. 
  [Conservative Party Candidate Andres Pastrana] The important 
thing is to give the Prosecutor General's Office resources so we 
can have true justice in Colombia. I would not modify it. If 
we have not been able to completely organize that office, the 
important thing is to provide it with the resources so we can 
have a real Prosecutor General's Office. We must not try to 
modify something that has not yet been implemented. 
  [General Miguel Maza, National Civic Consensus] The 
Prosecutor General's Office needs regulations. Why not increase 
its coverage? It has become deadlocked in the narcotics problem 
and in the voluntary surrender policy. 
  [Antonio Navarro Wolff, 19 April Movement Democratic 
Alliance] The prosecutor general deserves the powers he has. He 
is using them, albeit controversially. Nevertheless, he is 
undoubtedly making use of his powers, and that is good. He is a 
person who firmly believes in his convictions. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

